A few days ago I took my first steps — of many — towards my first bit of academic research. I am currently in an independent study with two professors and a fellow student at my University (Plymouth State University). This independent study began last year as a literature review. I had approached the Department chair seeking opportunities involving my major, sociology. I expressed to him my interests in statistical analysis and Geographic Information Systems. He then put me in contact with the two professors that I am working with currently. These professors told me of a project they would be doing in the near future and thought I would be a good student to aid them in their project. It was decided that the first step would be to conduct a semester long literature review.

Sherlock had that! (Both Doyle & Cumberbatch.) Without Ford’s men, but via Holmes’ Doyle-prescient, interlinked files (a rudimentary precursor to databases and the internet itself). Furthermore, it stemmed from his, very similar to Ford’s, attitude towards cluttering his mind with unnecessary facts. What had cosmological theory to do with crime? Then he needn’t nurse knowledge of even the simplest such facts, unless or until they were relevant to his life, his case, his focus. Few have such a tight focus and such impressive results as these two men, historical and fictional, did. But we could all use more focus than we have in this overwhelm era.

Okay so yes I partially agree. But what I mean is that statistics can only tell you what to expect, not what it will be in terms of an individual. So for instance if a study says 60% males have high mathematical ability in a particular population. Now an individual can fall anywhere. But the problem is even deeper. Studies often study human beings in certain aspects only. But in real life a host of factors both documented and non documented play a part in every aspect of developmental growth simultaneously. So studies like the one in example don’t look into it. An engine might aggregate large number of studies but there’s a qualitative difference between aggregating studies showing X influences Y where X and Y are various aspects of an individual and where every aspect is seen influencing each other (like brofenbrenner model). Moreover I don’t think this app looks into the larger more important aspect of development. Like only the care giver and the child’s personality is taken into account. What about the neighbors and neighborhood? The childs teachers friends schooling system country’s economic and political climate and so on and so forth. This are as detrimental to development as the individual itself. So yes statistics can act as guides but only when a therapist or a trained professional uses them in conjunction with the interaction with the actual child and situation. Evryone is unique and I do think that replacing the skills and more important the intuition of a trained human psychologist can only pass as acceptable in silicon Valley. Any psychologist who actually works with people can tell you that every client or participant needs to be researched in his own right. Here’s why psychology is not sociology or any other statistical science (if we are still stuck on that label).

Respectfully submitted, this is meaningless without a statistical baseline to compare it to — especially when the timeline is over 4 decades long. If you let any timeline play out long enough, statistically unlikely things happen: & you haven’t even gone the distance yet of showing whether or not this is statistically unlikely. How many unusual deaths were there during the Reagan years, or the Bush years? (the latter would be a better comparison given father and son presidencies, tho you might still have to extrapolate over 40 yrs) How many unusual deaths is an average person connected to in 40 yrs? (bad comparison since Clintons aren’t “average,” but helps anchor some kind of baseline) How many unusual deaths is an average “connector” (in the Malcolm Gladwell sense — someone who explicitly knows a lot of people) close to in a similar time frame?

Agreed! I am currently pursuing my PhD in physiology and I know too well what scientific research is like. I try to refrain from claiming my experimental findings as definitive because there’s too many factors involved and more than often, our experimental designs aim to look at one or two of them. Hence, experimental results rarely shows the whole picture. Only through extensive studies from multiple perspectives, a thorough meta analyses of all related findings then can we say that, yes, this is the most probable finding… and by probable, we agreed that at some point in the future, there is a possibility of being debunked as a result of better equipments and more rigorous experimental designs.

I appreciate your position, but I think you overestimate the rate at which programming skills will depreciate in value. The rise of Machine Learning and AI does not make a programmer unemployable. In fact, it makes them more valuable. Anyone can get their hands on pandas, scikit or Dato and leverage Python to run serious regressions with serious value. Furthermore, these new technological paradigms will still require APIs and people who possess the knowledge to interface with them. As to your position on gender roles, I cant really comment, and I don’t pretend to believe that promoting stem will break down gender norms. However, as a simpleton, I think everyone (women included) should learn to code (if they want to). It’s both fun and pays the bills. And I don’t see this changing anytime soon.

A few years ago I had a conversation with an awesome AI researcher at Google about the ML startup I was working on. He said (in a nutshell) that the approach we were taking probably would NOT succeed. It was a good idea, he said, but a couple big internet companies could potentially compete with us. Even though those companies had data that was less relevant (and less predictive) than the data my startup was working with — their data was orders and orders of magnitude larger in scale. He said “I’m just not sure you can ever beat huge amounts of data”. In his eyes, we didn’t even have a chance. Part of what allowed internet technology to advance so rapidly was because the barrier to contribute was very low.

Great ideas in this piece, thanks for sharing! At CloudFactory we see the frustration of data scientists and engineers having to prepare the data everyday. The statistic that says 60% of a data scientist’s time is spent on data prep is mind boggling and is surely slowing innovation. Part of the acceleration process has to come from building the infrastructure for data teams to access cloud labor who have expertise in the preparation process. But the key is making it easy to access and affordable, thereby democratizing the preparation step, so data scientists spend more time on innovation and less on organizing the past.
